      "title": "Classic 2×2 DiD",
      "chapter": "02-classic-did.html",
      "primary_method": "Two-period TWFE. In this case, it is exactly equivalent to first-difference OLS and non-parametric difference-in-means.",
      "alternatives": [
        "Doubly Robust DiD (`DRDID`) if you want to condition on covariates",
        "Non-parametric difference-in-means (exactly equivalent)"
      ],
      "assumptions": [
        "Parallel trends in untreated potential outcomes",
        "SUTVA (no spillovers, stable units, no hidden treatment variants)",
        "No anticipation in the pre-period"
      ],
      "caveats": [
        "With 2 periods and binary treatment, TWFE and first-differences are algebraically equivalent",
        "Consider `HonestDiD` (Rambachan & Roth) for sensitivity bounds on the parallel-trends assumption"
      ],
      "package": "fixest",
      "citation_keys": [
        "Angrist2009",
        "Roth2023"
      ],
      "code": "library(fixest)\nfeols(y ~ post_treat | id + time, data = df)",
      "flags": {
        "binary_only": true,
        "heterogeneity_robust": true,
        "no_dedicated_package": false
      }
    },
    "leaf_continuous_2p": {
      "type": "leaf",
      "id": "leaf_continuous_2p",
      "title": "Continuous-dose 2×2 DiD",
      "chapter": "08-continuous-treatment.html#sec-cgbsa-continuous",
      "primary_method": "Callaway, Goodman-Bacon & Sant'Anna (2024) `did` continuous branch. Report the level effect `ATT(d|d)` (dose $d$ vs no treatment, weak PT) and, when strong PT is defensible, the marginal effect `ATT'(d|d)` (dose-response derivative)",
      "alternatives": [
        "Dose-binned 2×2 DiD as a descriptive first pass",
        "Smoothed `ATT(d|d)` curve via kernel regression of 2×2 contrasts on dose"
      ],
      "assumptions": [
        "Level effects `ATT(d|d)`: weak parallel trends — untreated potential outcomes evolve in parallel across dose levels",
        "Marginal / dose-response effects `ATT'(d|d)`: strong parallel trends — the counterfactual trend is invariant to the realized dose",
        "No anticipation of the treatment or its dose",
        "Overlap across doses in the covariate and outcome support",
        "SUTVA: no spillovers, stable units, no hidden treatment variants"
      ],
      "caveats": [
        "A TWFE coefficient on a `post × dose` interaction is neither the level nor the marginal effect under heterogeneity — it is a dose-weighted average whose weights can be negative",
        "Report the full `ATT(d|d)` level curve, not a single scalar; add the `ATT'(d|d)` marginal curve when strong parallel trends is defensible",
        "With only two periods, the level and marginal curves are noisy — report pointwise and uniform confidence bands"
      ],
      "package": "did (continuous-treatment branch)",
      "citation_keys": [
        "CallawayGBSA2024"
      ],
      "code": "# Continuous-treatment DiD following Callaway, Goodman-Bacon, Sant'Anna (2024)\n# See https://pedrohcgs.github.io/posts/ for the canonical workflow",
      "flags": {
        "binary_only": false,
        "heterogeneity_robust": true,
        "no_dedicated_package": false
      }
    },
    "leaf_twfe_single_timing": {
      "type": "leaf",
      "id": "leaf_twfe_single_timing",
      "title": "Two-way fixed effects with common treatment timing",
      "chapter": "02-classic-did.html",
      "primary_method": "TWFE DiD and event-study around the common adoption date with unit and time fixed effects are the simplest estimator, although any other heterogeneity-robust estimators work too. ",
      "alternatives": [
        "Doubly Robust DiD if covariates support conditional parallel trends"
      ],
      "assumptions": [
        "Parallel trends in untreated outcomes",
        "No anticipation",
        "SUTVA"
      ],
      "caveats": [
        "With common timing and binary treatment TWFE is unbiased under parallel trends — heterogeneity-robust estimators are not strictly required",
        "If any units adopt at different times, move to the staggered branch"
      ],
      "package": "fixest",
      "citation_keys": [
        "Angrist2009",
